      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are fundamentally right that human judgment is necessary to identify and correct systemic errors that raw data might perpetuate, but giving humans the power to override decisions based on subjective \"social equity\" creates a dangerous loophole for arbitrary bias. If the committee can approve or deny cases based on their own moral compass rather than consistent rules, they will inevitably introduce new inconsistencies that are even harder to audit than the original algorithm. I propose we implement a \"safety valve\" protocol where humans can only intervene in statistically anomalous cases with full transparency and mandatory justification logs, rather than granting them blanket override authority.",
